{{Infobox person |name=Effie T. Brown |birth_date= |birth_place=[[United States]] |occupation=[[Film producer]] |education = [[Loyola Marymount University]] }}
'''Effie T. Brown''' is a film and television producer<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Effie Brown|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/536330/Effie-T-Brown|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lionsgate's Codeblack Taps Effie Brown to Produce 'Flyy Girl' Book Adaptation|author=Vlessing, Etan|date=February 25, 2015|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lionsgates-codeblack-taps-effie-brown-777670|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> known for such films as ''[[Rocket Science (film)|Rocket Science]]'',<ref name=NYT/> ''[[Real Women Have Curves]]'',<ref name=NYT/> ''[[Everyday People (film)|Everyday People]]'',<ref name=NYT2/> ''[[Desert Blue]]'',<ref name=NYT2>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Effie Brown Filmography|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/536330/Effie-T-Brown/filmography}}</ref> ''[[Dear White People]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Advanced Course in Diversity ‘Dear White People,’ About Racial Hypocrisy at a College|authorlink=A. O. Scott|author=Scott, A. O.|date=October 16, 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/17/movies/dear-white-people-about-racial-hypocrisy-at-a-college.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> and ''[[But I'm a Cheerleader]]''.<ref name=NYT/> She is seen in the fourth season of ''[[Project Greenlight]]'' as a producer on that season's film project ''[[The Leisure Class]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=‘Dear White People’ Producer Effie Brown Joins HBO’s ‘Project Greenlight’ (EXCLUSIVE)|author=Littleton, Cynthia|date=November 6, 2014|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/dear-white-people-producer-effie-brown-joins-hbos-project-greenlight-exclusive-1201349542/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 14, 2015|title=Project Greenlight Revealed Exactly Why Hollywood Still Has a Diversity Problem|author=Harris, Aisha|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/09/14/project_greenlight_s_new_star_is_effie_brown_the_premiere_revealed_exactly.html|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Damon criticised for interrupting black producer Effie Brown and explaining diversity|author=Saul, Heather|date=September 15, 2015|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/matt-damon-criticised-for-interrupting-black-producer-effie-brown-and-explaining-diversity-10501353.html|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|title=Tone-Deaf Matt Damon Ridiculed For Comment On Diversity In Hollywood. The diversity issue is best Damonsplained.|author=Boboltz, Sara|date=September 15, 2015|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/matt-damon-mansplains-hollywood-diversity_55f80f86e4b0c2077efbf413}}</ref>
== ''Project Greenlight'' controversy == In the fourth season premiere of [[Project Greenlight]], Effie Brown, along with director [[Peter Farrelly]] and actors [[Matt Damon]] and [[Ben Affleck]], met to decide which filmmakers would be chosen to direct a feature film for the show. Among the finalists considered were a directing team of an Asian American man, Leo Angelos, and a white woman, Kristen Brancaccio. Effie Brown expressed her support of this team, stating that <nowiki>"I would just urge people to think about whoever this director is, the way that they’re going to treat the character of Harmony, her being a prostitute,” Brown counters. “[She’s] the only black person, being a hooker who gets hit by her white pimp."</nowiki><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/09/14/project_greenlight_s_new_star_is_effie_brown_the_premiere_revealed_exactly.html|title=Project Greenlight Revealed Exactly Why Hollywood Still Has a Diversity Problem|last=Harris|first=Aisha|date=2015-09-14|work=Slate|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref> Damon, feeling frustration that the show had not properly cast more diverse filmmakers for the competition<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/03/movies/matt-damon-you-could-call-him-down-to-earth.html|title=Matt Damon: You Could Call Him Down to Earth|last=Ito|first=Robert|date=2015-12-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, responded that "when you’re talking about diversity, you do it in the casting of the film, not the casting of the show.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/09/16/matt-damon-screen-diversity_n_8145692.html|title=Matt Damon In Hot Water Over Diversity Remarks|date=2015-09-16|work=HuffPost UK|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>" Critics of Damon's comments stated that he was "mansplaining" and "whitesplaining" diversity to Effie Brown<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-34278195|title=Matt Damon 'sorry' over diversity row|date=2015-09-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-GB}}</ref> and accused him of being racially tone deaf.
