'''''The Colossus of Rhodes''''' is a 1954 oil painting by [[Salvador Dalí]]. It is one of a series of seven paintings he created for the 1956 movie [[Seven Wonders of the World (film)|''Seven Wonders of the World'']], each depicting one of the [[Seven Wonders of the Ancient World]], and shows the [[Colossus of Rhodes]], the ancient statue of the Greek titan-god of the sun, [[Helios]]. It was never used for the film, and in 1981 was donated by Georges F. Keller to its present location, the [[Kunstmuseum Bern]].

Dalí's rendering of the Colossus is heavily influenced by a paper, read in 1953 and published in 1956, by [[Herbert Maryon]], a sculptor and [[conservator-restorer|conservator]]
at the [[British Museum]]. Maryon had proposed a hollow Colossus that was made of hammered bronze plates, and stood aside the harbour rather than astride it. He also suggested that it had incorporated a hanging piece of drapery to give the statue a stable tripod base. All of these ideas were used by Dalí, whose depiction looks remarkably similar to Maryon's.

==Background==
''The Colossus of Rhodes'' arose out of Dalí's longstanding fascination with [[Hollywood]].{{sfn|King|2007|pp=59–60}} He described the industry as a surrealist medium, and termed [[Walt Disney]], [[Cecil B. DeMille]] and the [[Marx Brothers]] as "the three great American Surrealists"; in his 1937 essay ''Surrealism in Hollywood'', he declared that "Nothing seems to me more suited to be devoured by the surrealist fire than those mysterious strips of 'hallucinatory celluloid' turned out so unconsciously in Hollywood, and in which we have already seen appear, stupefied, so many images of authentic delirium, chance and dream".{{sfn|King|2007|p=59}} For the 1956 [[Cinerama]] film [[Seven Wonders of the World (film)|''Seven Wonders of the World'']], Dalí was commissioned to create seven paintings: ''The Colossus of Rhodes'',{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 689}} ''The Pyramids'',{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 693}}{{refn|group=note|The [[Gala-Salvador Dalí Foundation]] catalogue raisonné lists ''The Pyramids'' as a 1957 work.{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 693}}}} ''The Statue of Olympian Zeus'',{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 695}} ''The Temple of Diana at Ephesus'',{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 1149}} ''The Walls of Babylon'',{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 692}} and two versions of the same wonder, ''The Lighthouse of Alexandria''{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 690}} and ''Lighthouse of Alexandria''.{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 691}}{{sfn|Christie's|2016}}{{sfn|Sotheby's|2014}} In 1955 he also executed a similar copy, ''Walls of Babylon'',{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 1148}} and painted the last wonder, with ''The Mausoleum at Halicarnassus''.{{sfn|Christie's|2016}}{{refn|group=note|The Gala-Salvador Dalí Foundation catalogue raisonné does not list ''The Mausoleum at Halicarnassus''. On 13 May 2016 it sold for $1,325,000 at [[Christie's]], which led off its description by asserting that "Nicolas and the late Robert Descharnes have confirmed the authenticity of this work."{{sfn|Christie's|2016}}}} The paintings for the film were made, yet went unused.{{sfn|King|2007|p=60}}

Dalí's rendering of the Colossus is heavily influenced by a 1953 paper by [[Herbert Maryon]],{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|pp=53–54}} a sculptor and [[British Museum]] [[conservator-restorer|conservator]] particularly known for his reconstruction of the [[Sutton Hoo helmet]].{{sfn|Easby, Jr.|1966}}{{sfn|Maryon|1947}} On 3 December 1953 he presented a paper to the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]], also entitled ''The Colossus of Rhodes''.{{sfn|Maryon|1956|pp=72–75, 79–81}}{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}} It suggested that the statue was hollow, and stood aside the harbour rather than astride it.{{sfn|Maryon|1956|pp=72–75, 79–81}}{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}} Made of hammered bronze plates less than {{convert|1/16|in|adj=on}} thick, Maryon said, the Colossus would have been supported on its base by a hanging piece of drapery acting as a third point of support.{{sfn|Maryon|1956|pp=72–75}}{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}} Although the paper was not published until 1956,{{sfn|Maryon|1956}} two years after Dalí created his painting, [[Herbert Maryon#Colossus articles|newspaper articles about Maryon's 1953 presentation]] proliferated quickly and internationally.{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}}{{sfn|Badoud|2012|pp=34–36, 36 n.129}} In this context the painting "does not look extremely original."{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}} Dalí copied the likeness of the Colossus put forth by Maryon, clearly depicting hammered plates of bronze, and showing the same tripod structure with the statue supported by a piece of drapery.{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}}

==Description==
The painting is named after its subject, the [[Colossus of Rhodes]], a statue of the Greek titan-god of the sun [[Helios]] that was erected in the city of [[Rhodes]] by [[Chares of Lindos]] in 280 BC. The perspective is from below the statue's base, suggesting that the location of the viewer is set in a boat approaching the city, and emphasising the statue's massive size and height.{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=224–225}} A piece of drapery hangs around the waist of Helios and from his left arm, falling down to touch the ground behind him.{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}} The statue appears to be made of bronze, and had a segmented construction entirely composed of numerous individual plates.{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}}{{sfn|Badoud|2012|pp=34–36}} Helios raises his right hand to shield his eyes from the sun that he is the god of, giving "a vaguely Surrealist touch" to Dalí's work.{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=224–225}} In the lower right is signed "Salvador Dalí / 1954".{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 689}}

==Themes==
Dalí's greatest connection with surrealism came before 1940, when his works explored the subconscious and his perception of the world.{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=47–48}} ''[[The Persistence of Memory]]'', one of the works with which he is most identified, came in 1931,{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=35–36}} representing a decade that saw Dalí firmly within the avant-garde.{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=53, 57}} A move to the United States in 1940 brought new financial pressures, heightening his already marked showmanship and helping to occasion his relationship with Hollywood, and the end of [[World War II]] introduced a focus on the historical, scientific, and religious, to Dalí's work.{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=48–53}}

''The Colossus of Rhodes'' exemplifies Dalí's focus on cinema and the historical and scientific, and the loosening of his grip on surrealism.{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=224–225}} It is only marginally surrealist—the god of the sun shields himself from his domain—and resembles a movie poster,{{sfn|Shanes|2012|pp=224–225}} befitting a work commissioned for a movie.{{sfn|Christie's|2016}} Nor does Dalí offer a particularly original take on the Colossus, which is heavily influenced by Maryon's suggestions.{{sfn|de Callataÿ|2006|p=54}}

==Provenance==
The painting is in the collection of the [[Kunstmuseum Bern]], where it forms part of the 1981 Georges F. Keller bequest.{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 689}} Its accession number is G 82.007.{{sfn|Badoud|2012|p=37}} In the 1980s and 1990s it was exhibited in Europe and North America:{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 689}} at the [[Museo de Arte Moderno (Madrid)|Museo de Arte Moderno]] in [[Madrid]] during 1983, at the [[Staatsgalerie Stuttgart]] in [[Stuttgart]] during 1989, at the [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art]] in [[Fredensborg Municipality|Humlebaek]] from 1989 to 1990, and later that year in [[Montréal]], at the [[Musée des beaux-arts de Montréal|Musée des Beaux-Arts]].{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 689}}

Several of the other paintings in the ''Seven Wonders of the World'' series have come up for sale. ''The Statue of Olympian Zeus'' was sold by Sotheby's in 2009 for $482,500,{{sfn|Sotheby's|2009}} and is now in the collection of the [[Morohashi Museum of Modern Art]].{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 695}} In 2013 Sotheby's also sold ''The Temple of Diana at Ephesus'', for $845,000;{{sfn|Sotheby's|2013}} it is now in a private collection.{{sfn|Catalogue Raisonné 1149}} ''The Walls of Babylon'' was offered for sale by Sotheby's in 2014 with an estimate of £300,000–400,000, but was bought in.{{sfn|Sotheby's|2014}} Dalí's thematically similar 1955 paintings have also been auctioned. Christie's sold ''The Mausoleum at Halicarnassus'' for $1,325,000 in 2016,{{sfn|Christie's|2016}} and ''Walls of Babylon'' in 2001 for £168,750.{{sfn|Christie's|2001}}

